#### Part 2: Methods of Purifying Saltpeter (Potassium Nitrate) and Chemical Reactions

**Ancient Purification Method:**

The ancients commonly used the **recrystallization method** to purify saltpeter. Coarse saltpeter was dissolved in hot water, insoluble impurities were filtered out, and the solution was cooled to crystallize. This process was repeated multiple times to enhance purity.

**Modern Chemical Purification:**

Modern methods include **ion exchange** or **electrolysis**:

1. **Ion Exchange Method**: Utilizes ion exchange resins to adsorb impurity ions in the solution while retaining the nitrate ions (NO₃⁻), then elutes with a potassium nitrate solution to obtain high-purity potassium nitrate.
2. **Electrolysis Method**: Electrolyzes the potassium nitrate solution, using electrolysis principles to separate impurities and obtain high-purity potassium nitrate.

**Chemical Reaction:**

The purification of potassium nitrate mainly involves dissolution and crystallization:

\[ \text{KNO}_3 \text{ (s)} \leftrightarrow \text{K}^+ \text{ (aq)} + \text{NO}_3^- \text{ (aq)} \]

By controlling temperature and concentration, the crystallization of potassium nitrate can be achieved.

